The Model Context Protocol (MCP) allows AI applications to connect with external tools and data sources through a standardized client-server architecture [1]. Vercel provides a hosting environment for MCP servers that leverages Vercel Functions for efficient, scalable execution [2][3].

When deploying to Vercel, you should implement your server using the Streamable HTTP transport, which is the modern, recommended standard for remote MCP servers [4]. You can integrate the `mcp-handler` library to handle the protocol and tool execution automatically [2][3].

To connect an MCP host (like Cursor) to your Vercel-deployed server, point the client to your deployment URL followed by the path to your handler, typically `/mcp` [2][5].

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "my-server": {
      "url": "https://my-mcp-server.vercel.app/api/mcp"
    }
  }
}
```

Vercel-hosted MCP servers also support built-in OAuth for security, which you can implement using the `withMcpAuth` wrapper to ensure only authorized clients can access your tools [2]. For further security and compliance with the MCP specification, you can expose metadata endpoints within your `/.well-known/` directory [2].
